WEBVTT

00:00:00.200 --> 00:00:04.386
This walkthrough builds an interactive
account-risk assistant with Oracle AI

00:00:04.386 --> 00:00:10.433
Database, AG-UI, A2UI, the Oracle Database
MCP Java Toolkit, and a separate MCP App

00:00:10.433 --> 00:00:10.898
demonstration.

00:00:10.898 --> 00:00:16.014
The video is silent, with exact product
names preserved in its subtitles.

00:00:16.414 --> 00:00:18.680
The protocol map separates three
relationships.

00:00:18.680 --> 00:00:21.398
MCP connects an agent to tools.

00:00:21.398 --> 00:00:25.929
A2A connects independent agents, although
this single-agent demo does not implement

00:00:25.929 --> 00:00:26.382
A2A.

00:00:26.382 --> 00:00:31.818
AG-UI streams events and state between the
Java agent backend and its frontend.

00:00:31.818 --> 00:00:35.443
A2UI and MCP Apps provide different user
interface models.

00:00:35.843 --> 00:00:40.995
The default application now launches the
pinned Oracle Database MCP Java Toolkit

00:00:40.995 --> 00:00:43.337
over standard input and output.

00:00:43.337 --> 00:00:48.490
It initializes the MCP session, verifies
the server identity, and fails closed

00:00:48.490 --> 00:00:51.300
unless exactly five account-risk tools are
available.

00:00:51.700 --> 00:00:55.118
The Toolkit configuration enables
purpose-built reads, action identifier

00:00:55.118 --> 00:00:58.536
reservation, the procedure-backed write,
and a verification count.

00:00:58.536 --> 00:01:00.977
All database values are binds.

00:01:00.977 --> 00:01:05.371
Broad query, write, table, and
administration tools are not enabled.

00:01:05.771 --> 00:01:10.490
Oracle AI Database stores the accounts,
risk evidence, and audited follow-up

00:01:10.490 --> 00:01:10.962
actions.

00:01:10.962 --> 00:01:16.625
The approved MCP tool calls an input-only
procedure that validates inputs, locks the

00:01:16.625 --> 00:01:20.871
selected account, inserts one action, and
updates its status atomically.

00:01:21.271 --> 00:01:26.067
AG-UI streams standard run, text,
tool-call, state, and error events from

00:01:26.067 --> 00:01:28.944
the Java service to the browser.

00:01:28.944 --> 00:01:33.739
A2UI envelopes travel inside an AG-UI
custom event named a2ui.message, keeping

00:01:33.739 --> 00:01:35.657
transport and interface responsibilities
distinct.

00:01:36.057 --> 00:01:42.104
The browser accepts only A2UI version zero
point nine point one, the expected surface

00:01:42.104 --> 00:01:44.895
and catalog, and a small component
allowlist.

00:01:44.895 --> 00:01:50.941
Generated values enter the page as text,
so the agent cannot inject executable HTML

00:01:50.941 --> 00:01:51.871
or JavaScript.

00:01:52.271 --> 00:01:58.292
The separate MCP App now retrieves current
account rows from the Java service, which

00:01:58.292 --> 00:02:00.608
invokes the Toolkit's governed
find-at-risk-customers tool.

00:02:00.608 --> 00:02:05.240
The official basic host renders its
dashboard in a sandboxed iframe.

00:02:05.240 --> 00:02:09.408
Toolkit-labeled structured content crosses
the host bridge; database credentials do

00:02:09.408 --> 00:02:09.871
not.

00:02:10.271 --> 00:02:15.546
In the application, the user sets a risk
threshold and row limit.

00:02:15.546 --> 00:02:21.300
The AG-UI event rail shows run and MCP
tool activity, while A2UI renders

00:02:21.300 --> 00:02:24.657
selectable account cards, risk
explanations, and approval controls.

00:02:25.057 --> 00:02:30.720
Approval is bound to the actor, returned
account set, and a short-lived single-use

00:02:30.720 --> 00:02:31.192
identifier.

00:02:31.192 --> 00:02:36.382
Approve invokes the bounded MCP tools and
displays the committed action identifier.

00:02:36.382 --> 00:02:40.157
Cancel consumes the approval without
creating a database action.

00:02:40.557 --> 00:02:44.751
Each component keeps one clear
responsibility: MCP connects tools, A2A

00:02:44.751 --> 00:02:49.412
can connect independent agents, AG-UI
streams frontend events and state, A2UI

00:02:49.412 --> 00:02:53.606
describes trusted controls, MCP Apps
render rich sandboxed experiences, and

00:02:53.606 --> 00:02:57.800
Oracle AI Database governs data and
transactions through the Toolkit.

